Secondly, for items again like the folded sheets of metal or mature cheese, both of which have an unconsumed item needed for the combine (smithing hammer/dairy spoon) when there was a failure the hammer/spoon would be on the cursor not the product of the combine.  In that instance if it were macro'ed wouldn't the hammer/spoon then be placed where the macro told the mouse to put a finished product?  Meaning for the next combine the required hammer/spoon wouldn't be in the combine container because it had been mistakenly put where the finshed product was suppose to go?<br>
<br>
I'm not doubting you, that this could be done...I'm just not seeing how building a macro that could identify all the various out comes, products, unconsumed items, and failed alternate products  (an empty bottle for example when failing a Heady K combine, or the prepared fish AND bones produced from a single combine.) would really be all that much &quot;faster&quot; then just doing it the old fashioned way.  I don't even see how you could watch tv while &quot;casually&quot; watching the macro do it's thing in cases where there is an unconsumed item, or alternate products on failure.<br>
